nowing: Buddhism and Bhutanese Cinema -- tClaiming Space, Time and History in the Journals of Knud Rasmussen -- tQissa and Popular Hindi Cinema -- tIndex0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aStorytelling in World Cinemas, Vol. 2: Contexts addresses the questions of what and why particular stories are told in films around the world, both in terms of the forms of storytelling used, and of the political, religious, historical, and social contexts informing cinematic storytelling. Drawing on films from all five continents, the book approaches storytelling from a cultural/historical multidisciplinary perspective, focusing on the influence of cultural politics, postcolonialism, women's social and cultural positions, and religious contexts on film stories. Like its sister volume, Storytelling in World Cinemas, Vol. 1: Forms, this book is an innovative addition to the academic study of world cinemas.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 30. Aug 2021) 0aMotion picturesxHistory. 0aMotion picturesxPlots, themes, etc. 0aMotion picturesxPolitical aspects. 7aPERFORMING ARTS / Film & Video / History & Criticism.2bisacsh1 aArredondo, Isabel, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aBeus, Yifen T., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aChaudhuri, Shohini, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aClayton, Sue, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aDash, Robert, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aDempsey, Anna M., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aJelaca, Dijana, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aJoyce, Hester, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/re